column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Incompatible Product
column168: AGENT FOR SHIPPER ORDERED TWO CLEAN VACUUM TRAILER TO BE USED TO PUMP SALT BATH WATER FROM CERTAIN HOLDING TANKS.  THE TRAILERS WERE TO BE USED AS TEMPORARY STORAGE WHILE SHIPPER INSPECTED THE EMPTY HOLDING TANKS AND THEN THE SALT BATH WATER WAS TO BE PUT INTO THE HOLDING TANKS.  THE DRIVER SPOTTED THE FIRST TRAILER AT THE AGENT'S DIRECTION.  THE AGENT RAN HOSED INSIDE THE BUILDING AND TOLD THE DRIVER WHEN TO ACTIVATE THE PUMP.  WHEN THE FIRST TANK WAS EMPTY. THE AGENT RAN HOSES TO A SECOND TANK AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO START THE PUMP.  ABOUT TEN MINUTES LATER AN ORANGE VAPOR WAS NOTICED COMING FROM THE MUFFLER ON THE VACUUM PUMP. ABOUT TEN MINUTES MORE THE AGENT SAID TO SHUT DOWN, GO PARK THIS TRAILER AND BRING THE SECOND ONE. THE DRIVER TOOK THE FIRST TRAILER TO THE PARKING AREA AND HOOKED TO THE SECOND THEN HE NOTICED ORANGE VAPORS COMING FROM THE TRAILER VENT AND THE TRAILER FELT HOT.  THE DRIVER DROVE AWAY FROM THE FIRST TRAILER, LOCATED THE AGENT HAD TOLD HIM OF THE PROBLEM AND CALLED HIS TERMINAL.  THE AGENT CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  IT WAS THEN THAT THE MATERIAL ATE A HOLE IN THE PUMP AND THE PRODUCT RAN OUT ONTO THE GROUND. IT WAS LATER LEARNED THAT THE AGENT HAD COMBINED TWO TANKS CONTAINING SULFURIC ACID, HYDROCHORIC ACID, NITRIC ACID, HYDROFLUROIC ACID AND BORIC ACID SLUDGES INTO OUR MC307 TRAILER.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS ATTEMPTING TO TAKE THE TOP SKID OFF OF DOUBLE STACKED SKIDS OF FREIGHT.  THE TOP SKID PUNCTURED ONE OF THE PAILS ON THE BOTTOM SKID RELEASING LIQUID WHILE HE WAS MOVING THE SKID.  DAMAGED PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  EXTREME CAUTION MUST BE EXERCISED WHEN USING A FORKLIFT AROUND SKIDS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FREIGHT.

HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILLED DUE TO DRIVERS FAILURE TO CLOSE BLEEDER COMPLETELY.  LOPEZ ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSPORTATION WAS CONTRACTED TO PUMP MATERIAL FROM PIPELINE CONSTRUCTION SITE.  THE VIRGIN MATERIAL WAS TO BE SHIPPED ON A BILL OF LADING TO ARCO'S TERMINAL AT PIER "B' ST., LONG BEACH.  OUR DRIVER FAILED TO COMPLETELY CLOSE THE BLEEDER VALVE (MANUAL PRESSURE AND VACUUM RELIEF VALVE) - DURING TRANSPORTATION, MATERIAL SPILL OCCURRED - SURGE OF MATERIAL WITHIN CARGO TANK FORCES SMALL AMOUNTS OF MATERIAL INTO BLEEDER LINE - BLEEDER LINE IS A VERTICAL 3" PIPE WHICH LEADS INTO THE CARGO TANK INTO THE HIGHEST POINT OF THE TANKER TO ALLOW FUNCTION OF RELIEF - PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES WILL BE TO DOUBLE CHECK VALVE CLOSURE AND TRAIN IN SAFE OPERATION OF PROPER SAFETY PROCEDURES.  ATTACHED ARE COPIES OF BILL OF LADING AND MANIFESTS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF SPILL. ACTION TAKEN AT TIME OF INCIDENT OCCURRED, DRIVER CLOSED BLEEDER VALVE COMPLETELY - ALL MATERIAL CONTAINED IN THE BLEEDER LINE DRAINED ONTO THE STREET - CLEAN-UP ENSUED AS AUTHORITIES ASSESSED INCIDENT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM GENERAL ELECTRIC COMPANY LOCATED AT 7500 LINDBERG BOULEVARD IN PHILADELPHIA, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVE IN BRAINTREE, MA.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT THE PETRO TRUCK STOP LOCATED ON ROUTE 95 SOUTH IN ELKTON, MD TO CONDUCT A LOAD & TIRE CHECK.  DURING THIS INSPECTION, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE VEHICLE ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA.  THE DRIVER OPENED THE REAR DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER AND IDENTIFIED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS BEING TRANSPORTED.  HE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO AN 85 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THIS CONTAINER AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  AN INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER INDICATED THAT A SMALL PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED IN A SMALL CREASE LOCATED ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  IT IS NOT KNOWN WHAT CAUSED THIS CREASE.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF THE LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ENSCO, INC. LOCATED AT 309 AMERICAN CIRCLE IN EL DORADO, AR TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE ROAD IN CLEVELAND, OH IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS ONTO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  WHILE THE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION WERE AT THIS TRANSFER FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 16 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  A PORTION OF THIS MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT PAD WHERE THE VAN TRAILER WAS PARKED.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

ON TUESDAY AFTERNOON, JULY 16, 1996, THRU-PUT MARKETING (VENDOR) DELIVERED 9,000 GALLONS OF 22 DEGREE BAUME HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO THE BJ FACILITY. 5,000 GALLONS WERE PUMPED INTO BJ'S 15,000 GALLON STATIONARY STORAGE TANK. THAT BROUGHT THE STATIONARY TO FULL CAPACITY.  A BJ CARGO TANK WAS MOVED FROM THE VEHICLE PARKING AREA OF THE FACILITY TO THE ACID LOADING AREA AND THE REMAINING 4,000 GALLONS WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE VENDOR'S CARGO TANK TO THE BJ CARGO TANK.  THE BJ CARGO TANK WAS TO BE TEMPORARY STATIONARY STORAGE.  ACID IN THE 15,000 GALLON TANK WAS TO BE BLENDED WITH INHIBITORS AND WATER FOR DELIVERY TO CUSTOMERS THE NEXT DAY.  THE 4,000 GALLONS IN THE BJ CARGO TANK WOULD THEN BE PUMPED INTO THE 15,000 GALLON MAIN STORAGE TANK.  THE FACILITY CLOSED FOR THE DAY.  EARLY NEXT MORNING A SMALL LEAK (PIN-HOLE) WAS OBSERVED AT THE REAR OF THE BJ CARGO TANK.  A VAPOR CLOUD WAS FORMING AROUND THE ACID DOCK.  THE VENTURA FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  VFD SHUT OFF TRAFFIC ACCESS AROUND THE FACILITY AND TOOK CHARGE OF THE SCENE.  BY MID AFTERNOOON VFD AND A BJ EMPLOYEE GOT THE REMAINING ACID TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLED ACID WITH LIME AND CAUSTIC SODA.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE BJ FACILITY.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ASHLAND CHEMICAL LOCATED AT 2788 GLENDALE-MILFORD RD IN CINCINNATI, OH TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S CINCINNATI SERVICE CENER LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS ONTO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  WHILE THE CONTAINERS IN QUESTION WERE AT THIS TRANSFER FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1-2 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER INDICATED THAT THE GASKET USED A SEAL BETWEEN THE DRUM AND THE TOP LID FAILED ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE TOP LID.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED.

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING WEST ON MO 34, ENTERED THE CURVE AT EXCESSIVE SPEED. THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL WENT OFF THE NORTH SIDE OF THE ROAD.  DRIVER APPARENTLY STEERED BACK TO THE LEFT. ALL PROPERTY OWNERS NEAR THE SPILL WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AND WERE ASKED TO WATCH THEIR WELLS, PONDS AND STREAMS AND CALL DNR IF ANY SIGN OF GASOLINE WAS DETECTED.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN CAUTIONED TO WATCH SPEED AND DRIVE DEFENSIVELY TO AVOID OTHER INCIDENTS.

AFTER DONNING PROPER PPE, I CHECKED THE PH, WHICH READ 1, A STRONG ACID. MY RESPONSE SHEET SAID TO ADD SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE PH BECAME A NEUTRAL 7. M A DESMEDT CALLED TO THE SCENE.  IT WAS NOTED THAT A FROST LINE OF ABOUT 6" WIDE HAD FORMED AROUND THE DOME NEAR THE TANK SHELL.  ALSO NOTED WAS ONE DISCHARGE PIPE HAD FROZEN OVER. DAMAGED AND NON DAMAGED CONTENTS OF PACKAGE WERE PLACED INSIDE A 1A2 SALVAGE DRUM AND UPON RELEASE FROM FAA THE RECIPIENT CAME AND PICKED THEM UP.

PACKAGE WAS WET AND WHEN OPENED FOUND FIVE (5) PLASTIC BOTTLES OF UNKNOWN LIQUIDS.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT OF AT LEAST ONE OF THE BOTTLES THROUGH THE CAP.  PACKAGE WITH CONTENTS WERE PLACED INTO A 1A2 SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO OBTAIN AN MSDS.  THE MSDS STATES THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS BY IATA DEFINITION DANGEROUS GOODS.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AND HAS TAKEN SAMPLES OF THE LIQUID FOR TESTING.  THE PACKAGE HAS BEEN RELEASED BACK TO FEDEX FOR DISPOSITION.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING AN INBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE/ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED, AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL SEVEN METAL CANS CONTAINING WHAT APPEARED TO BE SOME TYPE OF PAINT. TWO OF THE CANS LID SEAL HAD FAILED ALLOWING LEAKAGE OF THE MATERIAL TO OCCUR.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND AN MSDS WAS FAXED TO THE FEDEX FACILITY WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED.  FROM THE INFORMATION LISTED ON THE MSDS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL DID EXHIBIT A LOW ENOUGH FLASHPOINT FOR IT TO BE CONSIDERED A REGULATED DANGEROUS GOODS COMMODITY. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. DURING SORT OPERATIONS THIS BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL THAT ONE CAN HAD A FRICTION LID WITHOUT ANY MEANS OF POSITIVE CLOSURE.  AN MSDS WAS FAX'D FROM THE SHIPPER INDICATING THAT THE MATERIAL WAS DOT REGULATED AS AN ADHESIVE, UN1133, WITH A FLASHPOINT OF 6 DEGREES F.  THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  I CALLED FAA SECURITY IN HNL AND SPOKE TO TONY TEPPIDINO.  TONY SAID HE WOULD INSPECT THE FREIGHT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE OF HER MATERIAL.  I SPOKE TO AMY DONAHOO AT THE SHIPPER LOCATION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATOR TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

AT 05:00, 22 JULY, WE RECEIVED THE SHIPMENT OF DRUMS ON AN AIRCRAFT PALLET INTO THE WAREHOUSE.  WHEN WE REMOVED THE PLASTIC COVER FROM THE PALLET IT WAS NOTED THAT TWO OF THE DRUMS WERE LEAKING AND APPARENTLY THE PLASTIC HAD BEEN PUSHED INTO THE HOLES TO ACT AS A CORK TO PREVENT LEAKING.  THE DRUMS WERE TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO AVOID ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE AND WERE REMOVED TO THE REAR DOCK OUTSIDE THE WAREHOUSE FOR VENTILATION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS SEVERAL EMPLOYEES COMPLAINED OF SKIN IRRITATION. THE METRO DADE HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED IN.  ONE EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED TO MERCY HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED.  THE HAZ MAT TEAM CLOSED THE WAREHOUSE AND RECOMMENDED THAT A HAZ MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY BE CONTACTED TO ENSURE THAT THE FACILITY WAS SAFE.  ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH AND RESTORATION, INC. WAS CONTACTED AND WAS ON SITE BY O500/23.  CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED BY 1015/23 AND THE FACILITY WAS REOPENED.  A TOTAL OF TEN EMPLOYEES REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION AND WERE AUTHORIZED.  THEY WERE TESTED, EYES AND SKIN FLUSHED WITH WATER AND ONLY ONE EMPLOYEE ELECTED NOT TO RETURN TO WORK FOR THE REST OF HIS SHIFT. ***** ALL EMPLOYEES AT THIS FACILITY MET WITH MANAGEMENT AND A MEMBER OF THE HAZ MAT CLEAN UP COMPANY TO ADVISE THEM OF WHAT HAD TRANSPIRED AND TO ALLEVIATE ANY FEARS THAT THEY MAY HAVE HAD REGARDING THE SPILL.  A NEW DANGEROUS GOODS PROCEDURE WAS DEVELOPED SO THAT IN THE FUTURE OUR EMPLOYEES WOULD BE ABLE TO REACT QUICKER TO CALL THE METRO DADE HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM AND TO AVOID ANY SPILLED MATERIALS.  ALL EMPLOYEES HAVE ATTENDED EITHER THE FULL LENGTH IATA D G CERTIFICATION COURSE OR A DANGEROUS GOODS AWARENESS TRAINING SESSION.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1245 HOURS ON JULY 8TH IN THE LIVERNOIS INTERMODAL TERMINAL, A K & D DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE CONTAINER, NONU 2663, HE WAS ABOUT TO PICK UP.  TERMINAL SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND IN TURN CALLED THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPERS MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND SERVICES CLEANED THE CONTAINER AND APPLIED SILICONE CAULK TO THE LEFT SEAL OF THE SIDE WALL AND BASE.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY COMPANY TOOK THE CAPTURED LIQUID AND CONTAMINATED SOIL FOR DISPOSAL.  THE APPARENT CAUSE OF THIS RELEASE IS THE FACT THAT THE 'SOLID' WASTE WAS NOT COMPLETELY DRY AND THE MOISTURE SETTLED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER DURING THE RAIL MOVEMENT AND FOUND AN OPENING/CRACK IN THE WELD SEAM TO ESCAPE.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THE FULL SHIPMENT CONSISTING OF TWO PALLETS WAS PICKED UP FROM THE SHIPPER ON WEDNESDAY, JULY 10, 1996. THE SHIPMENT WAS OFFLOADED ONTO OUR DOCK LATER THAT EVENING. ON THURDSAY, THE SHIPMENT WAS THEN RELOADED ON THE APPLICABLE VEHICLE FOR DELIVERY THAT AFTERNOON. ONE PALLET CONSISTED OF 40 BAGS OF SAND AND THE SECOND PALLET CONTAINED THE REMAINING ITEMS. THE AFFECTED SHIPMENT, A 5 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM, HAD BEEN PLACED ON THE BOTTOM AND POSITIONED OVER THE EDGE AND CORNER OF THE WOODEN PALLET SLAT. THE REMAINING ITEMS OF THE SHIPMENT WERE PLACED AROUND AND ON TOP OF THE AFFECTED SHIPMENT. BOTH PALLETS WERE SHRINK WRAPPED BY THE SHIPPER. THE DRIVER ON HIS ROUTE MADE A STOP AT A CUSTOMER SITE TO MAKE A FREIGHT PICKUP. TO ACCOMODATE AN NEW PICKUP, THE DRIVER HAD TO REPOSITION THE PALLET CONTAINING THE AFFECTED SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER WAS USING A NON-MOTORIZED PALLET JACK AND HAD JUST REPOSITIONING THE PALLET AND WAS LOWERING THE PALLET WHEN HE OBSERVED A SMOKEY/HAZY CLOUD AND DETECTED A CHEMICAL SMELL. HE IMMEDIATELY WALDED OUT OF THE VEHICLE. THE SHIPPERS OVERHEAD DOOR WAS CLOSED. THE DRIVER CALLED THE DISPATCHER AND THEN CALLED 911 TO INITIATE RESPONSE. ** FIRE CREWS FROM LOCAL COMMUNUTIES, INCLUDING A HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM FROM BLOOMINGTON, MINNESOTA RESPONDED AND ISOLATED THE SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO PERSONAL INJURIES. BAY WEST, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE SERVICE PERFORMED THE REMAINING CLEANUP, DECONTAMINATION AND THE DISPOSAL THE WASTE. THE ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH. FROM OUR INVESTIGATION, IT APPEARS THE WEIGHT OF THE AFFECTED PACKAGE ITSELF, OTHER PACKAGES STACKED ON TOP OF THE AFFECTED SHIPMENT, THE PROXIMITY OF ITS PLACEMENT POSITION ON THE EDGE AND CORNER OF THE PALLET SLAT COMBINED WITH A SLIGHT SHIFT OR MOVEMENT OF THE SHIPMENT CONTRIBUTED TO A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PLASTIC CONTAINER.

CSXT SWITCHED A TANK CAR TO THE ST MARYS FOR RR AT KINGSLAND, GA. ST MARYS REJECTED THE CAR BUT DID NOT INFORM ANYONE CSXT CUSTOMER SERVICE CALLED ST MARYS RR & FOUND OUT THE CAR WAS REJECTED ACCT. IT WAS LEAKING. CSXT'S MECHANICAL FOREMAN CALLED GENERAL AMERICAN TANK TO SEND A MOBILE UNIT TO MAKE REPAIRS, GENERAL AMERICAN REPLACED THE FILL HOLE COVER GASKET BECAUSE IT HAD "BLOWN OUT" THE CAR WAS PRESSURIZED TO CHECK FOR OTHER LEAKS. FINDING NONE, THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

ENGINEER VORMAN DID NOT GO TO HOSPITAL/HAVE ANY LOST TIME. SHIPPER RESPONDED AND FOUND MANWAY GASKET DEFECTIVE (IN 2 PCS.) GL BLANKENSHIP OF CSX WAS PRESENT DURING CHANGE OUT OF GASKET. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE BOLTS ON THE PHLANGE BELOW THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WERE LOOSE. THEY TIGHTENED THE PHLANGE BOLTS AND THE LEAKAGE STOPPED.

UTLX 12191 REPORTED TO SLOSH LIQUID FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED & THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER AUTHORIZED CSXT TO SENT A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE CAR. column168: WHILE TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON US ROUTE 23, NORTH OF CHILLICOTHE, OH, THE MC312 CARGO TANKER, CARRYING 5,000 GALLONS OF RQ WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID, NOS (NITRIC SULFURIC, AND HYROCHLORIC ACIDS), OVERTURNED ONTO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT THE CARGO TANK HAD DROPPED OFF THE PAVEMENT ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER AS HE WAS MOMENTARILY DISTRACTED BY A MESSAGE BEING TRANSMITTED OVER HIS PAGER.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AS IT ROLLED OFF THE ROAD WAY AND OVERTURNED.  THE IMPACT CAUSED DAMAGE TO THE FRONT MANWAY VALVE RESULTING IN THE SPILLAGE OF 148 GALLON OF THE WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID.  THE DRIVER REPORTED TO HIS DISPATCHER (ENVIRITE) WITHIN FIVE MINUTES OF THE INCIDENT.  THE DISPATCHER CONTACTED THE OHIO STATE POLICE WHO RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT ALONG WITH A LOCAL HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM.  ENVIRITE ALSO REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE ROSS COUNTY LOCAL EMERGENCY PLANNING COMMISSION (LEPC), OEPA, NATIONAL RESPONDER CENTER AND ODOT.

THE MATERIAL THAT WAS BEING HAULED WAS A SOLID.  THE MATERIAL THAT CAME FROM THE PACKAGE, I BELIEVE, WAS WATER THAT HAD "POCKETED" IN THE TARP OF THE ROLL-OFF AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE TAR MATERIAL WAS WITHIN THE WATER POCKETS.  7-7, INC WAS NOT AWARE OF THE MATERIAL COMING OFF OF THE TARP UNTIL CALLED BY THE PERSON WHO WAS FOLLOWING OUR VEHICLE.  HIS CAR WAS SPECKLED WITH TAR.  DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO CHECK TARPS FOR TRAPPED WATER PRIOR TO MOVEMENT.

AT 6:20 AM ON FRI. 7/19/96 A DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT A DRUM HE HAD PICKED UP THE PREVIOUS DAY HAD EXPANDED WHILE IN HIS TRAILER AND MIGHT BE UNSAFE TO TRANSPORT. THE DRUM WAS IN THE MIDDLE OF THE LOAD BUT DID APPEAR TO HAVE EXPANDED SUBSTANTIALLY AND THE DECISION WAS MADE TO NOT ALLOW THE TRAILER TO LEAVE THE YARD UNTIL THE PROBLEM WITH THE DRUM WAS RESOLVED. THE GENERATOR OF THE WASTE (IMI, INC.) WAS CONTACTED AND I SPOKE TO A MR. RON ZANGARI WHO CONFIRMED THAT THE DRUM CONTAINED WASTE NITRIC ACID IN A CONCENTRATION OF APPROX.. 20%. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE SUPERVISOR FROM OUR COMPANY WAS ADVISED OF THE PROBLEM AND TOOK CHARGE OF THE SITUATION. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO OBTAIN A POLY OVERPACK DRUM LARGE ENOUGH TO ACCOMMODATE THE EXPANDED DRUM, BUT BEFORE IT ARRIVED, THE PRESSURE IN THE DISTRESSED DRUM CAUSED IT TO SPLIT. APPROXIMATELY 30 TO 35 GALLONS OF THE WASTE NITRIC ACID SPILLED OUT OF THE RUPTURED DRUM OF WHICH APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS FELL TO THE GROUND UNDER THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY RESPONDED WITH FIRE, RESCUE AND HAZ-MAT TEAMS. MEANWHILE, THE AREA AROUND THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WAS DIKED WITH SPEEDY-DRI TO CONTAIN THE SPILL ON THE GROUND. AFTER CONFERRING AT LENGTH WITH THE FIRE DEPT. OFFICIALS ON THE SCENE, OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL BEGAN TO CLEAN UP INSIDE THE TRAILER, OVERPACK THE DAMAGED DRUM AND LATER REMOVED AND DRUMMED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM UNDER THE TRAILER. ALL WASTE FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS PROPERLY PACKED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A LICENSED T.S.D.F.

WHILE ATTEMPTING TO OVERPACK A 55-GAL. POLY CONTAINER INTO AN 85-GAL. OVERPACK DRUM, APPROXIMATELY 15-20 GALLONS OF MAGNESIUM HYDROXIDE LIQUID SPILLED ONTO THE PARKING LOT. THE 55-GAL. POLY DRUM DEVELOPED A TORN SEAM NEAR THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH RESULTED IN SPILLAGE OF THE MATERIAL. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND RE-CONTAINERIZED. THE CONTAMINATED SPILL AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED AFTER RECOVERY OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL (APP. 18M2). DRIVER HAS BEEN INSTRUCTED TO TAKE ADDITIONAL CARE IN OVERPACKING LEAKING CONTAINERS.

DRIVER ASKED CUSTOMER FOR ASSISTANCE. THEIR PERSONNEL PUT A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP POINT.  PRODUCT WAS EVAPORATED AT AN EQUAL RATE TO THE DRIPPING.  UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE CUSTOMER'S TANK OVERFLOWED.  THIS WAS NOT WITHIN THE WORK AREA OF THE TRUCK DRIVER. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL EFFECTED CLEANUP.

WHEN THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER TO START UNLOADING IT, HE NOTICED AN ODOR IN THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, HE DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER.  IT LOOKED LIKE IT WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING, BECAUSE SOME OTHER FREIGHT HAD FALLED ON IT AND CAUSED THE DAMAGE.  HE NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR, WE CLEANED UP THE SPILL, PUT THE DAMAGED FREIGHT IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND FILED A HAZ MAT REPORT.

ATSF RESPONDERS AND THE SHIPPERS CONTACTOR ASSESSED THE LOAD NUMEROUS WET DRUMS WERE REMOVED AND WIPED CLEAN.  THE CULPRIT DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A NAIL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM HEAD. ABOUT 55 GALLONS REMAINED IN THE DRUM.  AN OVERPACK WAS USED AND THE LOAD WAS REASSEMBLED.  BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS ADDED TO THE MINIMUM AMOUNT ORIGINALLY OBSERVED.  ALTHOUGH UNIT WAS RELEASED BY CONTRACTOR, THE DRAYMAN WHO REMOVED IT FROM THE RAMP HAD RETURNED IT ON ACCOUNT HE WAS FEELING ILL.  HE SUBSEQUENTLY RECEIVED AN EXAM AND WAS RELEASED WITHOUT HOSPITALIZATION.  A HIGH PRESSURE WASH WAS USED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT TO REMOVE ODORS.

column168: THE DERAMPING CREW NOTED TRAILER TO BE LEAKING, AS WELL AS PRODUCT ON DECK OF FLAT CAR.  TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO SAFE HAVEN DOCK AND PLASTIC SHEETING WAS PLACED TO FURTHER CONTAIN THE RELEASED PRODUCT.  A JOINT ASSESSMENT WAS MADE BY ATSF RESPONDERS AND BENEFICIAL OWNER'S RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. ONE OF 18 TOTES IN THE LOAD, ONE WAS FOUND TO HAVE SUSTAINED A FAILED POLY INTERIOR LINING.  THIS PERMITTED THE PRODUCT TO REACT WITH THE EXTERIOR STAINLESS STEEL RESULTING IN FAILURE OF THE PACKAGING.   ALL PRODUCT IN THE TOTE (200 GALS) WAS RELEASED.  SEVERAL LARGE HOLES WERE FOUND IN THE TRAILER FLOOR DUE TO THE ACID'S CORROSIVE REACTION.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE CLEANED AND RELOADED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR LOCAL DELIVERY.  THE DECK OF THE FLAT CAR WAS ALSO NEUTRALIZED.

column168: DURING THE SORT THIS SHIPMENT OF THREE BOXES, ONE WAS DAMAGED DUE TO OTHER FREIGHT. THE AIRBILL NUMBERS ON THE SUCCEEDING TWO SHIPMENTS ARE: 3789702402. WE RECOVERED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND ALONG WITH THE LEAKING BOX, PLACED ALL OF IT INTO A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER OF THE INCIDENT AND REQUESTED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET. THAT REQUEST STARTED A FAX PARADE WHERE MISINFORMATION ABOUNDED. THE FIRST FAX INDICATED IT WAS ISSUED BEFORE THE FIRST FAX MSDS SHOWED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS NOT REGULATED. WHEN WE DETERMINED THAT WE WERE NOT MAKING ANY PROGRESS AND STILL OUR QUESTIONS WERE NOT ANSWERED SUFFICIENTLY, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. SINCE THEN I BELIEVE THE FAA HAS CONFIRMED THAT MATERIAL IS IN FACT REGULATED, ONCE THE FREIGHT IS RELEASED WE WILL CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR A DISPOSITION.

A DOWELL ACID TRAILER WAS LOADED WITH 300 GALLONS OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID & 15 GALS OF XYLENE.  A DOWELL EQUIPMENT OPERATOR WAS CHECKING THE CONTENTS OF THE ACID TRAILER DURING THE PRE-TRIP INSPECTION.  AT THE TIME IT WAS DARK AND HE DIDN'T HAVE A FLASHLIGHT.  INSTEAD OF GETTING THE FLASHLIGHT, HE PULLED A CIGARETTE LIGHTER OUT OF HIS POCKET AND LIT IT TO SEE INSIDE THE TANK.  VAPOR FROM THE XYLENE IGNITED AND CAUSED A FLASH FIRE.  THE TRAILER AND CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER DID NOT IGNITE.  THE EQUIPMENT OPERATOR WAS WEARING FLAME RETARDANT COVERALLS AND RECEIVED BURNS TO HIS FACE, NECK, RIGHT FOREARM, AND RIGHT HAND.  ALL LIGHTERS TO BE TURNED INTO OFFICE WHEN EMPLOYEES SHOW UP FOR WORK.  EMPLOYEES TO BE ISSUED EXPLOSION PROOF FLASHLIGHTS TO PERFORM FLUID LEVEL CHECKS.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE UNLOADING LOCATION. WHEN HE WAS UNLOADING THE PUMP WOULD NOT PUMP OFF THE PRODUCT. DRIVER CALLED IN TO THE DISPATCHER FOR HELP AND A SECOND DRIVER WAS SENT OUT. WHEN HE ARRIVED TO THE CATRIM OF THE FIRST DRIVER HE ALSO TRIED TO PUMP OFF THE LOAD. THE PROBLEM WAS THAT THE CUSTOMERS HOSE HAD RUST AND CORROSION. THIS CAUSED BLOCKAGE AND PRESSURE TO BUILD UP AND THE FITTINGS BUSTED AND BROKE OFF RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 30 GALLONS OF JET A FUEL. DRIVER SHUT PUMPS OFF AND HE USED HIS SPILL KIT. WASTE CONTROL WAS CALLED OUT TO CLEANUP. DRIVER WAS NOT AT FAULT. THE FITTINGS ON THE PUMP WERE REPLACED AND THE CUSTOMER WILL CHECK THEIR EQUIPMENT TO PREVENT FUTURE RE-OCCURRENCE.

DRIVER WAS AT UNLOADING LOCATION. WHEN HE COMPLETED UNLOADING HE FAILED TO RECEIVE PRESSURE FROM THE TRAILER BEFORE UNHOOKING THE HOSES. THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF 1 GALLON OF HYDROCARBON. PRODUCT SPRAYED ON THE DRIVER. AFTER THE DRIVER CLEANED UP THE SPILL HE PROCEEDED TO GO TO THE DOCTOR. DRIVER WAS FINE HE WENT TO THE DOCTOR FOR PRECAUTION.  NO TIME WAS LOST OF WORK. DRIVER WAS VERBALLY COUNSELLED ABOUT PROPER UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

DRIVER WAS LOADING DIESEL NOT NOTICING THAT IT COULD ONLY HOLD 1000 GALLONS AND HE SENT 1325 GALLONS CAUSING THE TANK TO FILL UP. HE TRIED TO UNDO THE HOSE CLIP TO CLEAN OR DRAIN THE HOSE. THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF 1 GALLON OF DIESEL. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED BY THE DRIVER USING THE SPILL KIT. DRIVER WAS GIVEN VERBAL WARNING IN ORDER TO PREVENT RE-OCCURANCE.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP CLOSURES OF 6 OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OF SITE DISPOSAL AT A LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. THE CONTAINERS INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE WERE RECEIVED BY THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY AND IMMEDIATELY PROCESSED. EACH OF THE 6 CONTAINERS FOUND TO BE LEAKING WERE INSPECTED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE PLACEMENT OF THE GASKETS USED TO ACHIEVE A SEAL WERE INCORRECTLY PLACED ALLOWING THE MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. DRIVERS WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING OR DAMAGED. IN ADDITION, THE FACILITY THAT OFFERED THESE CONTAINERS FOR SHIPMENT HAVE BEEN ALERTED TO THE PROBLEM AND HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ON ALL FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

column168: WHEN OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CUSTOMERS LOCATION, HE LEARNED THAT THEIR STORAGE TANK WAS NOT IN OPERATION. THE CUSTOMER ASKED OUR DRIVER IF THE TRAILER COULD BE DROPPED AND LEFT UNTIL REPAIRS TO THE STORAGE TANK WERE COMPLETED. OUR DRIVER CONTACTED COMPANY OPERATIONS. OPERATIONS INFORMED THE CUSTOMER THAT THE TRAILER WOULD NOT BE DROPPED AND SUGGESTED THAT THE PRODUCT BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. THE CUSTOMER TOLD OPERATIONS THEY HAD ANOTHER METHOD TO GET THE UNIT UNLOADED. THE CUSTOMER HAD OUR DRIVER ATTEMPT TO OFF LOAD APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF THE AQUA AMMONIA INTO A STORAGE TANK INSIDE THE BUILDING. THE CUSTOMERS EMPLOYEES AND OUR DRIVER DID ATTEMPT TO OFF LOAD INTO THIS SMALL TANK. THEY FOUND THAT THE PLUMBING WAS CLOGGED AND PRODUCT COULD NOT FLOW INTO THE TANK. THE CUSTOMER THEN INFORMED OUR DRIVER THEY HAD YET ANOTHER PLAN.  THE CUSTOMER CONTACTED A LOCAL CARRIER WHO WOULD SUPPLY A CARGO TANK TRAILER, TO BE USED AS STORAGE, SO THE FIRST TRAILER COULD BE OFF LOADED. WHEN THE SECOND CARGO TANK ARRIVED, THE TWO DRIVERS POSITIONED THE UNITS TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT. THE ORIGINAL DRIVER, OUR DRIVER, WAS TO DO ALL THE TRANSFERRING. THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS TO BE DONE BY AIR PRESSURE SUPPLIED BY AN AIR COMPRESSOR ON THE FIRST ORIGINAL CARGO TANK. AFTER OUR DRIVER SUCCESSFULLY GOT THE PRODUCT TO FLOW, BOTH DRIVERS STEPPED BACK AWAY FROM THE UNITS AND WAITED FOR THE TRANSFER TO BE COMPLETED. THE DRIVERS WERE STANDING NEAR THE CENTER OF THE SECOND TRAILER TALKING WHEN THEY OBSERVED THE TRANSFER HOSE JUMP, INDICATING THE FIRST TRAILER WAS EMPTY. BEFORE THEY COULD MOVE, A SURGE OF AIR FROM THE FIRST TRAILER COMING THROUGH THE TRANSFER HOSE, PUSHED AN AIR BUBBLE THROUGH THE PRODUCT CAUSING SOME OF AQUA AMMONIA LIQUID TO COME OUT THE OPEN DOME LID ON THE SECOND TRAILER. THE LIQUID AQUA AMMONIA THAT CAME OUT THE OPEN DOME LID SPRAYED UP AND IT RAINED DOWN ON TOP OF BOTH DRIVERS. BOTH DRIVERS WERE SPRAYED BY THE RAINING AQUA AMMONIA. A THIRD DRIVER WHO WAS NEAR BY UNLOADING HIS TRUCK, LED BOTH DRIVERS TO A SAFETY SHOWER AND STARTED TO RINSE THEM OFF. TWO CUSTOMER EMPLOYEES, WHOM WERE OUTSIDE THE BUILDING BUT NEAR THE SPRAYING AQUA AMMONIA, WERE EXPOSED TO AQUA AMMONIA FUMES. BOTH DRIVERS WERE TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM FOR CHECKUPS.

AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 PM ON JULY 23, 1996, A RELEASE OF METHYL TERT-BUTYL ETHER (MTBE) FROM A RAILROAD TANK CAR, NATX 29120, OCCURRED AT TEXACO'S BAKERSFIELD REFINERY. THE RELEASE OCCURRED AS REFINERY OPERATIONS STAFF, A LOADER BLENDER "A" (LBA), PREPARED TO UNLOAD THE RAILROAD TANK CAR. THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY THE FAILURE THE VALVE HOUSING OF THE RAILROAD CAR'S TOP UNLOADING VALVE, A THREE-INCH JAMESBURY VALVE, DURING THE INITIAL STEPS OF THE MTBE UNLOADING PROCESS. A SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION ATTRIBUTED THE FAILURE OF THE VALVE TO MISSING PACKING ASSEMBLY HOLD-DOWN NUTS, AS SHOWN BY THE ATTACHED BILL OF LADING, ARCO CHEMICAL COMPANY LEASED RAILROAD TANK CAR NATX 29120 TO DELIVER MTBE TO THE BAKERSFIELD REFINERY. PRIOR TO UNLOADING THE RAILCAR, THE LBA COMPLETED THE BAKERSFIELD PLANT'S "TANK CAR INSPECTION CHECKLIST" AND THE "GENERAL INSPECTION ON ARRIVAL CHECKLIST". THE LBA UNSEALED THE DOME LID ON THE RAILCAR AS PART OF THE "GENERAL INSPECTION UPON ARRIVAL" PROCEDURE. HE ATTACHED THE VAPOR PRESSURING/DEPRESSURING HOSE TO THE RAILCAR. HE COMPLETED DEPRESSURING THE VAPOR SPACE TO THE AREA 1 FLARE. THE LBA THEN ATTACHED THE TWO-INCH DIAMETER UNLOADING HOSE TO THE RAILROAD TANK CAR. HE DID THIS BY UNSCREWING THE THREE-INCH MALE NATIONAL PIPE THREAD (MNPT) PLUG FROM THE TOP OF THE THREE-INCH JAMESBURY BALL VALVE. HE HAD ALREADY CONNECTED THE OTHER END TO THE SWEDGE REDUCER TO A DRY BREAK CONNECTION FOR THE TWO-INCH HOSE. THE LBA THEN PRESSURIZED THE RAILROAD TANK CAR TO 40 TO 60 PSIG WITH MAKE-UP GAS FROM THE NATURAL GAS HEADER. THE LBA COMPLETED ALL HOSE CONNECTIONS TO THE RAILROAD TANK CAR AND BEGAN OPENING THE UNLOADING VALVES. THE FIRST VALVE OPENED BY THE LBA  WAS THE THREE-INCH JAMESBURY VALVE ON THE RAILROAD TANK CAR. AS THE LBA OPENED THIS VALVE, THE PACKING BLEW OUT. HE WAS NOT INJURED. THE PRESSURE IN THE RAILROAD TANK CAR PUSHED MTBE UP THE DRAIN PIPE AND OUT THE BODY OF THE JAMESBURY VALVE. THE LBA EVACUATED THE AREA AND SOUNDED THE ALARM. BAKERSFIELD PLANT STAFF INITIATED AN INCIDENT COMMAND SYSTEM AND A BAKERSFIELD PLANT RESPONSE TEAM. KERN COUNTY FIREFIGHTERS, AND A KERN COUNTY HAZMAT RESPONSE TEAM RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT. WATER AND FOAM WERE APPLIED TO THE RAILROAD TANK CAR AND THE SURROUNDING AREA TO REDUCE THE RISK OF FIRE. ALL NEARBY PLANT OPERATIONS AND ELECTRICAL EQUIPMENT WERE ALSO SHUT DOWN TO FURTHER REDUCE THE RISK OF FIRE. NO FIRE RESULTED FROM THE INCIDENT. ONCE ALL PRESSURE INSIDE THE RAILROAD TANK CAR WAS RELIEVED, THE HAZMAT TEAM SEALED THE LEAKING VALVE. FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT, BAKERSFIELD PLANT STAFF DISCUSSED THE NEED FOR AN IMPROVED RAILROAD TANK CAR MAINTENANCE PROGRAM WITH ARCO CHEMICAL STAFF. BAKERSFIELD PLANT STAFF AND ARCO CHEMICAL STAFF HAVE HELD PERIODIC MEETINGS TO DISCUSS ARCO'S RAILROAD TANK CAR MAINTENANCE PROGRAM AND OTHER CUSTOMER SERVICE ISSUES. THESE MEETINGS HAVE RESULTED IN NOTICEABLE IMPROVEMENTS TO ARCO'S RAILROAD TANK CAR FLEET USED TO DELIVER MTBE.

column168: AS THE FREIGHT WAS BEING UNLOADED, A STRONG ODOR WAS NOTICED.  THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT.  THE BOX WAS OPENED AND WE FOUND A 4 LITRE CAN OF AMMONIA SOLUTIONS. I SPOKE WITH CHRIS MURCH FROM GOLD PLATING, WHO INDICATED THAT ON OCCASION, JOE SOKE REALLY WORKS FOR TECH 2000.  THIS COMPANY IS NO RELATION TO GOLD PLATING,  EXCEPT THAT GOLD PLATING ALLOWS TECH 2000 TO SHIP ON THEIR FEDEX POWERSHIP (CONJECTURE:  THIS SEEMS VERY SUSPICIOUS, BUT ANYTHING IS POSSIBLE.)  I SPOKE TO JOE SOKE WHO SAID HE DOES NOT SHIP LIQUIDS VERY OFTEN, ESPECIALLY ON FEDEX.  JOE WAS ALSO UNAWARE THAT FEDEX WAS AN AIRLINE.  JOE SAID THAT HE WAS UNAWARE THAT FEDEX FLEW THEIR FREIGHT & WAS EQUALLY CONFOUND THAT WE WOULD FLY HIS FREIGHT TO PHX, RATHER THAN THRUCK IT.  I LEFT A MESSAGE FOR THE RECIPIENT.  THE FAA, MAX CROWLEY-PHX CASFO, HAS INSPECTED THE FREIGHT.   ONCE THE FREIGHT IS RELEASED WE WILL ASK THE SHIPPER TO FAX A DG DECLARATION TO PHX SO THAT THE FREIGHT MAY BE DELIVERED OR RETURNED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, OR OTHER INDICATOR THAT WOULD LEAD US TO BELIEVE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.   THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDECLARED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1320 HOURS, RONNIE SNEAD DRIVER FROM MXI TRUCKING SIGNED IN THE FACILITY FOR THE PURPOSE OF PICKING UP WASTE FROM OUR FACILITY. THE TRUCK WAS LOCATED TO THE EAST PLANT WAREHOUSE LOADING DOCK #2.  ONCE AT THE LOADING DOCK, DRIVER SNEAD OPENED THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER ONLY TO FIND LEAKAGE OF AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE COMING FROM EITHER A 300 GALLON TOTE FILLED WITH WASTE OR A 55 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE PICKED UP FROM ANOTHER GENERATOR'S LOCATION.  WALTER SCOTT, LEAD WAREHOUSEMAN NOTIFIED BOB SCHROEDER, ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER THAT THERE WAS A LEAK FROM A TRAILER WHICH WAS LOCATED IN DOCK #2.  UPON MR. SCHROEDERS ARRIVAL AND ASSESSMENT OF THE SITUATION, SPILL PILLOWS WERE APPLIED AND HE NOTIFIED GERRY SAMSON - FACILITY EMERGENCY COORDINATOR TO ACTIVATE NORAMCO'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (ERT).  AT 1335 HOURS THE ERT WAS NOTIFIED TO RESPOND TO THE COMMAND POST FOR BRIEFING OF THE SITUATION.  **** MAINIFESTS WERE COLLECTED FROM THE DRIVER AND IT WAS LEARNED THAT THE TRAILER CONTAINED EIGHT (8) 300 GALLON TOTES OF WASTE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL - UN 1263, ONE (1) 300 GALLON TOTE OF WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID (ACETONE/BUTYL ACETATE) - UN 1993 AND FOUR (4) DRUMS OF THE SAME MATERIAL.  IT WAS NOT DETERMINED AT THIS TIME EXACTLY WHAT MATERIAL AND HOW MUCH HAD BEEN LOST ONLY THAT A SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNT HAD BEEN DETECTED ON THE FLOORING OF THE TRAILER.  MSDS WERE GATHERED AND MR. RON PANASIEWICZ, GENERAL MANAGER (INCIDENT COMMANDER) ALONG WITH THE TEAM MADE A DECISION THAT SINCE THE MATERIAL WAS NOT NORAMCO'S THAT WE NOTIFY OUR HAZARDOUS INCIDENT CONTRACT TEAM H.M.H.T.T.C. TO RESPOND AND HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  NORAMCO'S ERT'S ROLE IN THIS INCIDENT WOULD ONLY BE DECON AND ASSIST H.M.H.T.T.C. ****** 13:55 HRS.  GERRY SAMSON NOTIFIED THE CONTRACT EMERGENCY RESPONDERS TO RESPOND.  AT THE SAME TIME, CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED FOR THE PURPOSE OF INQUIRY AS TO WHAT HAZARDS WE WERE DEALING WITH.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTED AS THE EMERGENCY CONTACT FOR THE SHIPPERS VAN WATERS & ROGERS (VWR).  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED VWR OF THE INCIDENT. ***** 14:20 HRS.  WILMINGTON FIRE DEPT, BATTALION CHIEF GILES WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION.  WE DID NOT REQUIRE A RESPONSE FROM THEIR AGENCY BUT GILES RESPONDED TO THE COMMAND POST.  14:29 HRS.  H.M.H.T.T.C., ALAN ECKER ARRIVED AT OUR FACILITY AND WAS INFORMED OF THE SITUATION.  AT THIS TIME ECKER RECOMMENDED A LEVEL "A" ENTRY AND CONFIRMED THAT NORAMCO'S TEAM WOULD ASSIST IN DECON.  14:44 HRS.  STAN FRAWLY FROM MXI CONTACTED THE COMMAND POST AND INFORMATION WAS EXCHANGED IN REFERENCE TO THE MATERIAL INVOLVED AND LIABILITY ISSUES.  A LIABILITY RELEASE FORM WAS FAXED TO MXI FOR THEIR SIGNATURE AND RETURNED BY FAX TO H.M.H.T.T.C. ****** 14:50 HRS.  DELAWARE NATURAL ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES (DNREC) SGT. DENNIS WALLACE WAS NOTIFIED OF OUR INCIDENT.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS FROM DNREC WOULD NOT RESPOND.  WE WERE ADVISED THAT CHRIS BERLIN REPRESENTATIVE FROM THAT OFFICE WOULD RESPOND TO SURVEY THE SITUATION, ACT AS A CONSULTANT AND ASSIST IF NEEDED.  15:

HE ADVISED THAT IN HIS ABSENCE CONTACT SHOULD BE MADE WITH LORI BURG, 319-244-7255.  HE ALSO ADVISED WILLINGNESS TO CALL RESCAR TO ASSIST IN MITIGATION IF NECESSARY. PACKING GLAND NUT LOOSE ON GAUGING DEVICE.  5.  3 BOLTS LOOSE ON BASE OF SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  6.  REMOVED, INVERTED AND REPLACED "O" RINGS ON SRV.  FOLLOWING ABOVE REPAIRS CAR WAS FOUND TO BE SECURE AND WAS RELEASED TO RIP TRACK FOR BRAKE REPAIRS.

column168: ON JULY 25, 1996, AT 11:45 P.M., OUR DRIVER, EDWARD WHITE WAS EASTBOUND ON I-40 IN HOLLADAY, TN WHEN HE WAS NOTIFIED OVER THE CB BY ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER THAT HIS MUD FLAP WAS ON FIRE.  OUR DRIVER STOPPED RIGHT AWAY AND TRIED TO PUT THE FIRE OUT, AS DID THE OTHER DRIVERS.  THE HOLLADAY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND BY THE TIME THEY ARRIVED THE TIRES AND TRAILER WERE ON FIRE.  THE FIRE WAS SO HOT THAT IT MELTED THAT AREA OF THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY 40-50 POUNDS OF RQ, HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID N.O.S., CLASS 9, NA 3077, PG III (KO61) (EMISSION CONTROL DUST/SLUDGE FROM PRIMARY PRODUCTION OF STEEL IN ELECTRIC FURNACES) FELL TO THE GROUND.  ******* THE TENNESSEE EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, THE HOLLADAY VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT WERE ON THE SCENE ALONG WITH FERGUSON-HARBOUR INC WHO DID THE CLEAN-UP.  JACK GRAY TRANSPORT, INC. NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE, REPORT #353449.  MANIFEST # AR 805613.

column168: I WAS CALLED TO THE MIDDLE OF THE HAMPTON BELT FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE, WAS MARKED WITH CORROSIVE 8 DIAMOND LABEL.  I PUT BOX IN SPILL TRAY AND CARRIED TO PROCESSING AREA.  CONTAINED THE CONTAMINATED MATERIAL AND PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP, THE CAPS ON THE BOTTLES BECAME LOOSE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE.  ISP CARD FILLED OUT, BOTTLES NEED TO HAVE SEALS AND CAPS TAPED.

RESPONDED TO SPILL ON SORT AISLE AND FOUND LEAKING BOX CLEARLY MARKED WITH UPS-5 PART FORM AND DOT FLAMABLE LIQUID DIAMOND LABELS ON PRIMARY BELT. NO ONE HAD TOUCHED THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  INSPECTION OF PACKAGE REVEALED 3 CAN OF "RUBBER CARE" THAT HAD BEEN SEVERELY DENTED, ONE OF WHICH WAS LEAKING.  WHAT HIT THE PACKAGE IS UNKNOWN BUT IF THE REQUIRED 2 INCHES OF PACKING HAD BEEN PRESENT THE CANS WOULD NOT HAVE RUPTURED.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN ACCORDANCE WITH UPS HAZMAT PROCEDURE AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP

I RESPONDED TO A SPILL BY DOOR 32 IN THE LOAD LINE WEARING MY PPE.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE AND REFERRED TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  I USED CLAY ABSORBENT TO SOAK UP EXCESS LIQUID AND CARDBOARD.  I DISPOSED OF THE MATERIAL THROUGH THE DMP PROCEDURE.  I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.

RESPONDED TO SPILL BY DAVE SHERDON (L K CENTER MGR) IN PPE, TRANSPORT PACKAGE TO REWRAP CENTER.  CONSULTED DECISION TREE WEARING PPE REFERRED TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  TESTED SPILL WITH PH PAPER (PH14) USED ACTIVATED CARBON OVER SPILL.  RETESTED THE SPILL (PH7) USED CLAY ABSORBENT TO SOAK UP EXCESS LIQUID.  DISPOSED MATERIAL THROUGH DMP PROCEDURES.  I DECONTAMINATED MY PPE.
PACKAGE WAS DROPPED BY HOURLY AT BROWN BELT SLIDE. RESPONDER DONNED PPE AND PROCESSED PACKAGE PER DMP USING THE DECISION TREE AND THE CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: CSXT'S RAIL YARD IN AUGUSTA, GA, REPORTED TWO TANK CARS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLETS.  THE TRAINMASTER CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE AND THEY RESPONDED WITH A TEAM TO REPAIR THE CAR.  THE CONSIGNEE FOUND THAT ON BOTH CARS THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVES WERE NOT TIGHTLY CLOSED & THE OUTLET CAPS WERE LOOSE.  THE CONSIGNEE CLOSED & SECURED THE OUTLET VALVE & TIGHTENED THE OUTLET CAPS.  THE LEAKS STOPPED.  THE CARS WERE REPAIRED & RELEASED FOR DELIVERY. SEE REPORT NO 96080336 A

MR. WESTLAKE CHECKED HIS BAG IN DAL.  DURING THE FLIGHT, A CAN OF SPRAY PAINT LEAKED OUT IN HIS BAG/CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER HAD CRACKS ON THE BOTTOM AND THE PAINT LEAKED OUT IN BIN "F" OF THE AIRCRAFT.  WHEN THE AIRCRAFT WAS UNLOADED IN HOU IT WAS NOTICED SOME PAINT HAD LEAKED ON THE BAGS.  THE BAGS WERE UNLOADED IN THE CLAIM AREA AND THE CONTAINER LEAKING THE PAINT WAS FOUND.  THE CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED, THE CUSTOMER ADVISED OF THE SITUATION AND ALL NECESSARY INFORMATION WAS TAKEN.  MR. WESTLAKE WAS INFORMED WE WOULD HAVE TO KEEP THE CONTAINER FOR FURTHER INFORMATION AND WOULD BE RELEASED TO HIM IN A FEW DAYS.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS CLEANED OUT, THE PROPER DEPARTMENTS AND PEOPLE WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: 09:45 HAZ MAT COORDINATOR TONY FRYE REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN THE HAZ MAT FEED AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  HAZ MAT COORDINATOR RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL I FOUND A FIBREBOARD BOX, WITH THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WET.  I OPENED THE TOP OF THE BOX AND FOUND 6 INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  ONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES DUE TO AN UNSECURE CLOSURE.  I RESEALED THE CLOSURE, RESEALED THE BOX AND REPACKED THE SHIPMENT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT ON TO DESTINATION.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE ARE AS FOLLOWS:  FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS N.O.S., (ISOPARAFINIC HYDROCARBON MIXTURE), 3, UN 1993, PG III, PKG INST 309.  FLASHPOINT 107 DEGREES F.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED INSIDE THIS PACKAGE.  CLEAR OF SCENE:  10:35.

WE RECEIVED SHIPMENT AT CORPUS ALREADY DAMAGED AND SPILLED.  SHIPPER SHOULD HAVE INDICATED SHIPMENT AS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND INCLUDED SAFETY (M.S.D.S.) DATA SHEET. **** THE EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE ON 7-23-96 ARE AS FOLLOWS.  WE RECEIVED AT OUR CORPUS TERMINAL ON ONE OF OUR TRAILERS A SHIPMENT OF FORMALDEHYDE WHICH HAD SPILLED ONTO HALF OF OUR TRAILER FLOOR. WHEN THE DRIVERS NOTICED A PUNGENT SMELL AND A WHITE POWDER ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER THEY NOTIFIED THE DOCK FOREMAN WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED ME. THE DOCK FOREMAN AND THE DRIVERS WERE WONDERING IF POWDER WAS HAZARDOUS. I ASKED TO SEE PAPERWORK ASSOCIATED WITH SHIPMENT AND NOTICED NO INDICATION OF IT BEING HAZARDOUS.  I THEN INSTRUCTED DRIVERS TO PULL SHIPMENT FROM TRAILER SHRINK WRAP SKID AND DELIVER TO CUSTOMER.  THE DRIVERS SOLOMON DIA AND TOMAS PANTOJA THEN PROCEEDED TO DO SO.  THE THEN PROCEEDED TO LOAD SHIPMENT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER FOR DELIVERY.  TOMAS PANTOJA DELIVERED SHIPMENT TO CELANESE IN BISHOP, TEXAS.  THE SHIPPING AND RECEIVING CLERK MENTIONED TO DRIVER TOMAS PANTOJA THAT THEY WERE EXPECTING THIS DAMAGED FREIGHT.  THE CUSTOMER THEN PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD FREIGHT WHICH CONSISTED OF 47 PAPER BAGS, 50 LBS EACH, AND ONE SUPER SACK ON ANOTHER PALLET.  THE DRIVER, TOMAS PANTOJA, NOTICED THAT THE INDIVIDUALS UNLOADING SHIPMENTS WERE WEARING RESPIRATORS.  THAT AFTERNOON ABOUT 5;00 P.M. OF THE SAME DAY I INSTRUCTED DRIVER MIKE GARA AND TOMAS PANTOJA TO SWEEP OUT TRAILER AND COLLECT MATERIAL IN TRASH CAN.  I HELPED THEM SWEEP IT UP AND SWEEP THE DOCK.  THE NEXT DAY, 7-24-96, EVERYONE CAME TO WORK AS USUAL AND WE ALL CARRIED OUT OUR ROUTINE ASSIGNMENTS.

JEFF MCLAUGHLIN HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN OPEN THE TWO FIBERBOARD BOXES AND DISCOVERED THAT THEY BOTH CONTAINED 2 - 2 OUNCE BOTTLES OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE 5.25 SOLUTION. INSIDE EACH BOX IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OF THE TWO PLASTIC BOTTLES HAD LEAKED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS DUE TO BROKEN LIDS. THESE FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE NOT MARKED OR LABELED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THESE TWO BOXES WERE NOT SPEC PACKAGES. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL INVESTIGATION AND RELEASED BY THE FAA.

column168: MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW, WAS CONTACTED BY MYO, NORTH PLATTE, ADVISING THAT CARMEN NOTED LEAK FROM TANK CAR EDCX 6202, UPON ARRIVAL INSPECTION OF TRAIN NLNO-20.  INSPECTION OF TANK CAR EXCX 6202, REVEALED LEAK BETWEEN MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE AND MANWAY NOEL, 'B' END OF CAR.  4 OUT OF 20 MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED ON OLD ENGINE LEAD TRACK.  TIGHTEN THE 4 MANWAY BOLTS, USING 3/4 INCH SOCKET WRENCH, WHICH SLOWED DOWN LEAK.  ALSO, USED TORQUE-MULTIPLIER ON ALL MANWAY BOLTS, WHICH ALSO SLOWED DOWN LEAK.  WITH THE AID OF SCOTT BRACEY, RISKCAR INC, HUDSON, COLORADO, USED PNEUMATIC WRENCH ON MANWAY BOLTS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  TOM FLORES, CHEMTREC, AND GEROLD MARTIN, EL DORADO CHEMICAL, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D A LOW WAS CONTACTED BY CAR FOREMAN THAT TANK CAR GATX 99852 WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR.  CAR WAS ISOLATED OUTSIDE OF THE ONE SPOT REPAIR BUILDING.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN, WITH THE STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND LOOSE.  ALSO, 2 OUT OF 8 MANWAY SWING BOLTS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  PROPERLY SECURED ALL FITTINGS WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  MILLIE RIVERARA, KERN OIL AND ALICE MARTIN, COASTAL CHEM, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SAHM LIBBY WAS ADVISED BY DEBBIE MARTIN, UNION PACIFIC MOTOR FREIGHT SUPERVISOR, SEATTLE, THAT TRAILER CSXZ 231366 HAD BEEN OPENED BY THE FRA TO INSPECT FOR BLOCKING AND BRACING.  FURTHER ADVISED THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED ACCOUNT INSUFFICIENT BLOCKING AND BRACING AND 3 - 55 GALLON DRUMS WERE LYING ON THEIR SIDE.  NO LEAK WAS DETECTED.  LIBBY ADVISED MS. MARTIN TO CONTACT CLAIMS AT PALESTINE, TX. AND REQUEST THEY ARRANGE TO HAVE THE TRAILER RELOADED.  JERRY PERRY, CLAIMS, WAS CONTACTED AND RON BENNETT, ITS INSPECTOR, INSPECTED THE TRAILER IN QUESTION 07/25/96 NOTING NO BLOCKING OR BRACING AND 1 OF THE 3 DRUMS LYING ON ITS SIDE TO HAVE A SMALL LEAK. AFTER BENNETT'S INSPECTION IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE TRAILER BE DRAYED TO ARTIC OVERSEAS PACKING, 4800 DENVER AVE. S. TO BE REWORKED.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HRS., 07/26/96 LIBBY WAS ADVISED THAT RICHARD PERSON, GENERAL MANAGER, ARTIC OVERSEAS PACKING, SEATTLE, HAD FOUND ONE 55 GALLON DRUM OF 3 - 55 GALLON DRUMS OF RESIN SOLUTION TO BE LEAKING.  LIBBY ADVISED MR. PERSON TO OVERPACK THE DRUM AND RELOAD IT INTO THE TRAILER AFTER CLEANING THE FLOOR.

THE TRAIN CREW OF UPRR LIHO-05 WAS NOTIFIED THAT CONTAINER KNLU 292917 HAD AN OPEN DOOR.  THE TRAIN WAS STOPPED JUST EAST OF RAGLEY, LOUISIANA AND INSPECTED.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THREE 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD FALLEN FROM THE CONTAINER ON TO THE FLATCAR TTWX 992803.  ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID.  UP44 REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY T M ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  ROBINSON UPRIGHTED THE LEAKING DRUM AND THIS STOPPED THE LEAKAGE.  THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED FLAMMABLE, UN1866.  THE DRUMS WERE LABELLED SHELL ADDITIVES, SHELLSWIM 11T, ORIGIN FRANCE, FLAMMABLE UN 1886, GROSS 191 KG, NET 174 KG. THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS WERE STENCILLED, SHELL 1227/3072, SHELLSWIM 11T, HOUSTON, TX, B/N 10005602.  THE FLAT CAR WAS SET OUT ON A SIDING AT MILE POST 524 AND THE TRAIN PROCEEDED ON.  ROBINSON REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, INCIDENT #96-2676.  ROBINSON CONTACTED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL AND REQUESTED SERVICES FOR OVERPACKING THE DAMAGED DRUMS AND RESECURING THE CONTAINER.  EMTECH RESPONDED AND OVERPACKED THE THREE DAMAGED DRUMS.  DUE TO SHIFTING OF THE REMAINING DRUMS IN THE CONTAINER, THE OVERPACKED DRUMS COULD NOT BE REPLACED IN THE CONTAINER.  THESE DRUMS WERE TAKEN BY EMTECH ONTO HOUSTON FOR LATER DELIVERY TO DESTINATION.  THE CONTAINER WAS THEN SECURED BY EMTECH FOR MOVEMENT ONTO DESTINATION.  THE FLATCAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column168: AT 1330 HRS ON 7-2-96, MYO GARY HADDOCK HAD REPORTED TO CTS MGR LERCH THAT TANK CAR ACFX 83790 WAS LEAKING AND THE ABOVE REFERENCED CAR WAS BEING SET-OUT IN TRACK #294.  UPON ARRIVAL, MGR LERCH NOTED CAR LOADED WITH DIESEL FUEL TO LEAKING FROM THE THREADS OF THE "B" END, 2 INCH INTERIOR HEATER COIL PIPE NIPPLE EXTENDING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY A FAILED INTERIOR HEATER COIL PIPE.  AFTER DETERMINING THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MGR LERCH PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT, WHICH WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON EVERY 2 HOURS.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE.  AT 1600 HRS, MGR LERCH CONTACTED AND ADVISED CHARLIE WALTERS, SENIOR PURCHASING DIRECTOR OF FUEL AND LUBRICANTS.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE BY MR WALTERS, THAT PRO-OIL, CONTRACTED FUEL TRANSPORTERS WOULD OFF LOAD THE CAR AND TRANSPORT FUEL OIL TO KANEB PIPELINE TERMINAL, LOCATED SOUTH OF BAILEY YARD.  OFF LOADING OF THE CAR BEGAN AT 1800 HRS AND WAS COMPLETED WITH THE LAST LOAD AT 0300 HRS ON 7-2-96.  A TOTAL OF 20,760 GALLONS HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED WITH CREDIT GIVEN TO UPRR, PER ARRANGEMENTS MADE BY MR WALTERS.  CAR WAS THEN SPOTTED AT THE DIESEL SHOP NORTH LOAD BOX TRACK AND REMAINING FUEL WAS DRAINED FROM THE INTERIOR HEATER COILS. ******* AFTER COILS WERE DRAINED, CAR WAS STENCILED LEAKY TANK, DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIRED.  AN "x" WAS SPRAYED ON THE LEAKING HEATER COIL PIPE NIPPLE AND PLACARDS WERE REVERSED TO READ RESIDUE.  CAR WAS BAD ORDERED BY CAR DEPT AND SHIPPED TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS.  NOTIFICATIONS:  1520 HRS, 7-2-96, KANEB PIPELINE, RON WALL, MGR PRODUCT MOVEMENT; 1613 HRS, CHEM-TREC, JEFF BOTWINICK, #45611.

UPRR YARDMASTER POTTER REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX 58261 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  IT WAS SENT TO YARD TRACK FOR REPAIR.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND LEAKAGE NEAR THE BOTTOM OUTLET AND UNDER THE "B" END AT THE BOLSTER.  THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED AND ADVISED.  VAN WATERS ROGERS (CONSIGNEE) LOCATED AN EMPTY TANK, GATX 90915, WHICH WAS SPOTTED OUTSIDE THEIR FACILITY IN DALLAS.  THE SHIPPER CONTRACTED WITH EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL TO TRANSFER THE LADING.  THE LADING WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TRUCKS (COB CITY TRUCKING) AND THEN TRUCKED ACROSS TOWN TO BE OFF-LOADED INTO GATX 90915.  TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED AT 0200 HRS.  CONTAMINANT WAS NEUTRALIZED ON SITE.  CAR WAS STENCILED AND RELEASED TO BE SHOPPED BY OWNER.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, D A LOW WAS CONTACTED BY FRED BRYANT, FRA/HAZ/MAT INSPECTOR, THAT TANK CAR GATX 39738, WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM VALVE ON TOP.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT TOP OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN TWO COMPLETE TURNS WITH STUFFING BOX PACKING GLAND LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  SECURED VALVE AND PACKING GLAND WHICH STOPPED LEAK.  GEOFF ASNES, CLEAN HARBORS, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.  IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT INTACT SEALS; CFF 142448 & CHI 01174 WERE REMOVED TO MAKE REPAIRS AND AFTER REPAIRS, SEAL; UP-U-209336 WAS APPLIED.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, STABILIZED OR HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: AT 1945 HRS ON 7-6-96, CORRIDOR MGR HAD CONTACTED CTS MGR LERCH.  HE ADVISED, CONDUCTOR S L BARRCLAUGH REPORTED TANK CAR UTLX 200552, TRAIN SLNPCX-02, WAS FOUND LEAKING.  HE FURTHER ADVISED THAT TRAIN HAD RUN OUT OF TIME AT FARR, NE. MP 255.6.  UPON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH NOTED THE SIDES OF THE CAR TO BE WET WITH PRODUCT AND TRACES OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND BELOW THE CAR.  INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY REVEALED THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD RUPTURED DUE TO HYDRAULIC SURGE.  MGR LERCH REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISK WITH THE SPARE FRANGIBLE DISK LOCATED WITHIN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY AND RELEASED THE CAR/TRAIN WITHOUT FURTHER DELAY.  THERE WERE NO REPORTED INJURIES, WATERWAYS OR DRAINS AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE. NOTIFICATIONS:  2317 HRS, 7-6-96, CHEM-TREC, BOB WIBLE, #45703; 2330 HRS, UPRR EMG, STEVE MCNAUGHTON; 0905 HRS, 7-8-96, NE D.E.Q., JIM BOROVICH, #070896-JB-0905; 1050 HRS, DEGUSSA CORP, DAVE HARMS, SENIOR INDUSTRIAL HYGENIST/SAFETY SPECIALIST.

column168: ON 071696 MTO S DINKINS NOTIFIED CTS MGR M KELLY THAT THE ABOVE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED LEAKING BY ONE OF THE YARD CREW.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE YARD KELLY INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS ONLY TWO THIRDS OF THE WAY CLOSED AND THE VALVE HAD NOT BEEN SECURED.  THE PLUG IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS ONLY HAND TIGHT ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SEEP OUT OF THE CAR AND ON TO THE GROUND.  KELLY CLOSED AND PROPERLY SECURED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ON TO ITS DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.

UPRR MTO GARY SCOTT REPORTED THAT TANK CAR GATX 26080 WAS LEAKING WHEN MOVED.  CAR WAS SET OUT FOR CORRECTION.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THAT THE RUPTURE DISC HAD BURST.  THE 100# BS&B DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A LIKE KIND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  KAREN, SINCLAIR OIL (918) 584-5025, WAS ADVISED.  TRACY JACKSON, CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AT 1730 HRS, REPORT #46013.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: ON 071896 AT 0730 HRS MTO B STREETY ADVISED CTS MGR. M. KELLY THAT A TRAIN CREW WORKING IN THE YARD AT ANGLETON, TX. HAD SMELLED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE ABOVE TANK CAR.  MR. STREETY STATED THAT THE CAR BELONGED TO PHILLIPS PETROLEUM AT SWEENEY, TX. AND THAT HE HAD NOTIFIED THEIR RESPONSE TEAM OF THE PROBLEM.  MR. STREETY ADVISED THAT THEY WERE ENROUTE TO REPAIR THE CAR.  AT 0945 HRS D. YARBROUGH WITH PHILLIPS CONTACTED KELLY AND ADVISED THAT THEY HAD INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE VAPOR VALVE WAS NOT PROPERLY CLOSED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  YARBROUGH ADVISED THAT THE VALVE WAS SECURED AND THE CAR WAS READY TO BE RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 071896 S FISHER WITH UP DAMAGE PREVENTION SERVICES CONTACTED CTS MGR M KELLY AND ADVISED THAT A DERAILMENT HAD OCCURED IN THE YARD IN PALESTINE, TX AND THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE ABOVE PRODUCT HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE ABOVE CAR ON TO THE GROUND.  KELLY CONTACTED EMTECH EMERGENCY SERVICES IN FT WORTH, TX AND REQUESTED THEIR ASSISTANCE IN CLEANING UP THE SPILL.  ON 071996 KELLY MET WITH EMPLOYEES OF EMTECH AND SUPERVISED THE SPILL CLEAN UP.  THE PRODUCT WAS COMPLETELY RECOVERED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM TO AWAIT DISPOSAL.  THE CAR WAS REPAIRED AND ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: DEAN C COOPER MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY FRANK VALDEZ, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THE WEST END SWITCH CREW OBSERVED A TANK CAR LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE IT WAS BEING HANDLED IN A CUT OF CARS DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, ROBERT SPINKS, WHO INSPECTED THE TANK CAR, AND FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM A BURST FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND ASSEMBLY WITH BAFFLE, WHICH IS MOUNTED ADJACENT TO THE MANWAY, AND WITHIN THE WORK PLATFORM AREA WAS DISASSEMBLED AND THE BURST DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND BS&B STAINLESS/TEFLON FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED, AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGSS INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT AND TYPE OF PRODUCT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS, WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER AS INFORMATION.

RESPONDED TO DOOR 65.  USED DECISION TREE AND FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, LIQUID WAS COMPLETELY CONTAINED AND ABSORBED BY BOX.  BROUGHT TO DMP CAGE CUT OFF SATURATED BOX PARTS AND PROCESSED ACCORDING TO DMP GUIDELINES.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D. A. LOW WITH THE COMPANY OF FRED BRYANT, FRA INSPECTOR, NOTED A STRONG ODOR PLUS A HISSING NOISE COMING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 58978.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT GATX VACUUM RELIEF VALVE HAD FAILED.  PLUGGED VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. JOHN HENRY, CLEAN HARBORS, WAS NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTION.  SEALS CHI 01538 AND CHI 001163, WAS REMOVED FROM PROTECTIVE HOUSING TO COMPLETE REPAIRS. AFTER REPAIRS, SEAL UP-U-209381 WAS APPLIED.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 HOURS ON JULY 23 IN GOODMAN YARD, FRA INSPECTOR A. P. SCHEIDER NOTED VAPOR COMING FROM GATX 33489. THE INSPECTOR DETERMINED THAT THE ODOR EMITTED FROM A DEFECTIVE PACKING FOR THE OPERATING ROD. column168: PAIL WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED. EXAMINATION OF THE PAIL REVEALED A SMALL PUNCTURE WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE. THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.

BOXES WERE STORED OUTSIDE BEFORE BEING LOADED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  WATER COLLECTED IN BETWEEN THE CARDBOARD AND THE PLASTIC LINER.  WHAT ACTUALLY LEAKED OUT WAS JUST THE WATER.  THE LINERS IN THE BOXES WERE NEVER BROKEN. EVENTS:  THE TRUCK BROKE DOWN BECAUSE OF A FUEL PROBLEM.  WHEN THE STATE TROOPER SHOWED UP HE INSPECTED THE TRAILER WITH THE CLEAN VENTURE DRIVER JOHN KOROVICH.  AS THEY INSPECTED THE LOAD THEY FOUND THAT TWO OF THE BOXES HAD SPLIT OPEN AT THE BOTTOM.  THE TROOPER CONTACTED HIS BARRACKS AND THE BARRACKS CORPORAL CALLED CYCLECHEM AND SPOKE TO PAUL WITTE, THE OFFICE MANAGER.  PAUL THEN CONTACTED CLEAN VENTURE'S SPILL RESPONSE SUPERVISOR, CHARLES LAKATOS.  THE CLEAN VENTURE TEAM SHOWED UP ON SITE AT 2200 AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL BY 2300.  THE MATERIAL THAT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL WAS SPEEDY-DRI AND THAT WAS TRANSPORTED TO ENVIRITE AND DISPOSED IT THERE.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE NUMBER WAS CALLED AND THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO A MR. GARNEAU.  THE REPORT # GIVEN IS 353966.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: CONTAINER WAS LOADED AT PATI WAREHOUSE IN CHICAGO AND RENDERED TO HYUNDAI MARINE AT SANTA FE RAIL YARD IN CHICAGO. RAIL YARD INSPECTED CONTAINER AND REQUIRED ADDITIONAL BLOCKING AND BRACING WHICH WAS DONE ON RAIL SIGHT BY DRIVER. CONTAINER MOVED VIA RAIL TO LOS ANGELES. SANTA FE RAILROAD DISCOVERED HAZ MAT SPILL IN COMMERCE CALIFORNIA RAIL YARD AND CONTACTED CAROTRANS CHICAGO OFFICE ON JULY 30, 1996. CAROTRANS CHICAGO OFFICE CONTACTED SHIPPER (RILEY INDUSTRIES - TIM WONNELL) TO REPORT INCIDENT. RILEY INDUSTRIES ADVISED CAROTRANS CHICAGO THEY WOULD SENT THEIR OWN HAZMAT TEAM TO SIGHT TO INVESTIGATE AND CLEAN UP SPILL. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK UNDER SUPERVISION OF STEVE LONG OF SANTA FE RAILROAD. RILEY INDUSTRIES CONTACTED CARTTRANS CHICAGO ON JULY 31, 1996 AND ADVISED THAT SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND CONTAINER WAS SAFET AND AVAILABLE FOR PICK-UP. RILEY ADVISED THAT ALL 36 DRUMS WERE TO BE RETURNED TO THEIR FACILITY IN INDIANAPOLIS, TN. CAROTRANS CHICAGO CONTACTED CAROTRANS LAX AND REQUESTED THAT ARRANGEMENTS TO BE MADE TO DRAY CONTAINER TO CAROTRANS LAX FACILITY TO OFF LOAD DAMAGED CARGO AND RETURN TO RILLEY. CAROTRANS LAX CONTACTED CSX DRAYAGE TO HAVE CONTAINER PICKED UP AT SANTA FE AND BE BROUGHT TO CAROTRANS FACILITY IN RANCHO DOMINGUEZ, CA. FOR UNLOADING. CSX DISPATCHED DRIVER TO MAKE PICK-UP. DRIVER WAS OVER COME BY SMELL AND REFUSED TO MOVE CONTAINER. DRIVER BECAME ILL AND WAS SENT TO CLINIC FOR MEDICAL ATTENTION. DRIVER WAS RELEASED AFTER EXAMINATION AND ADVISED HE COULD RETURN TO WORK. CSX DISPATCHED ANOTHER DRIVER TO SANTA FE TO PICK-UP CONTAINER AND DELIVER TO CAROTRANS LAX. CONTAINER WAS OFF LOADED AT CAROTRANS LAX. CAROTRANS LAX RETURNED ENTIRE SHIPMENT TO RILLEY INDUSTRIES VIA OVERNIGHT TRANSPORTATION TRUCKING COMPANY. CAUSATION OF SPILL WAS DETERMINED TO BE PUNCTURE OF BOTTOM OF DRUM BY NAIL PROTRUSION FROM FLOOR OF CONTAINER. FUTURE SPILLS OF THIS KIND MIGHT BE AVOIDED BY INSPECTING CONTAINER FLOORS FOR NAILS AND OTHER SHARP OBJECTS. ALL PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO RILLEY. RILLEY MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR CLEAN-UP SO ANY HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL WOULD BE HANDLED THROUGH THEM OR THEIR HAZMAT CLEAN-UP COMPANY.

column62: Corrosion - Exterior; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: PAUL BARNES RESPONDED TO WEST PRIMARY BAY 49 TO CLEAN UP A CORROSIVE SPILL.  HE USED HIS DECISION TREE WHICH LED HIM TO HIS CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  HE CONTAINERIZED THE LEAKING PACKAGE IN A SPILL CONTAINER AND BROUGHT IT TO THE DOT CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  I NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE, ABSORBED IT WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT, PROCESSED THE DAMAGED PORTION THROUGH THE DMP, AND RTS'ED THE BALANCE.

column42: PHOSPHORUS, WHITE OR YELLOW DRY OR UNDER WATER OR IN SOLUTION
column168: SPECIALIST CTS RICHARD TUFTS WAS NOTIFIED AT 1115 HRS 07/24/96 BY SPECIAL AGENT BOB BRYANT, THAT ST LOUIS FIRE DEPT AND REPS FROM MONSANTO WERE AT IVORY YARD DUE TO PHOSPHORUS CAR THAT HAD BEEN ON FIRE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT HAD BEEN EXPOSED AT BASE OF SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD SPONTANEOUSLY IGNITED AND THAT THE SWITCH CREW HAD CALLED NONSANTO AT APPROX 0530 HRS.  UPON SPECIALIST TUFTS ARRIVAL AT SCENE, MONSANTO CREWS WERE PREPARING TO CHANGE OUT THE SRV.  NO ADDITIONAL PRODUCT HAD ESCAPED AND NO ADDITIONAL FIRE WAS OBSERVED.  SPECIALIST TUFTS ASSISTED MONSANTO CREWS WITH SRV REPLACEMENT.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY MONSANTO, BASED UPON RESIDUE ASH, THAT APPROX 1 TSP. OF PRODUCT HAD BECOME INVOLVED IN THE FIRE AND THERE HAD APPARENTLY BEEN NO LEAKS.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SRV WAS NOT DEFECTIVE.  A DEBRIEFING WAS HELD AT MONSANTO FOLLOWING THE INCIDENT.

CGI DOCKMAN, KAHLID STARKS, WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER WHEN HE DISCOVERED ADHESIVE ON THE FLOOR COMING FROM THE BACK OF THE SKID.  WE UNLOADED THE FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THE SKID TO GET TO THE SPILL.  MR. STARKS CLEANED UP THE SPILL.  FREIGHT SUPERVISOR, DAVID HEFFERNAN, SENT THE TRAILER TO THE SHOP FOR CLEANING.  ONE BOX OF THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE OSAD BAY (3 OUT OF 6 GALLONS FROM THE BOX WERE LEAKING).  MATERIAL IS BEING HELD ON DOCK PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
